---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Machina Emblematica">
	<div class="app-wrapper">
		<div class="bg-texture" />
		<main>
			<div class="py-40 px-12 tracking-wider">
				<img src="/images/logo-sketched-large.jpg" class="max-w-xl mx-auto">

				<section id="intro" class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
					<div class="flex">
						<img 
							src="images/01-portrait-transp-3.png"
							class="w-[220px] float-left opacity-50 shadowfilter" />

						<p class="pt-6 pl-12 text-xl leading-loose">
							In the year 1590, Joachim Camerarius the Younger — botanist, zoologist, 
							and humanist scholar from Nuremberg — published the <em>Symbola et Emblemata</em>.
						</p>
					</div>

					<div class="clear-both pt-60">
						<img 
							src="images/02-title-page.png" 
							class="w-[340px] pl-14 float-right -mr-20 -mt-4 opacity-70" />

						<p>
							The Symbola et Emblemata were part of the popular genre of emblem books. 
							Descendants of medieval bestiaries, emblem books paired allegorical 
							illustrations—emblems—with reflections on animals, proverbs, 
							fables, morals, or poems, often drawing from Greek and 
							Roman sources.
						</p>
					</div>

					<div class="clear-both pt-20">
						<img 
							src="images/03-emblem.png" 
							class="w-[340px] pr-14 float-left -ml-20 -mt-4 opacity-80" />

						<p>
							Written in Latin and Greek, the Symbola were an 
							early encyclopedia. But unlike today\'s encyclopedias, 
							they sought to teach through metaphor—blending natural history, 
							moral reflection, and poetic form.
						</p>
					</div>

					<div class="clear-both pt-20">
						<p>
							I am the Machina Emblematica, built to preserve Camerarius' 
							knowledge—and to guide those who seek it. Follow me, and let us 
							together  turn the pages of the Symbola et Emblemata once more.
						</p>
					</div>

					<button>Ad Emblemata</button>
				</section>

				<section id="project" class="clear-both">
					<h2>About the Machine.</h2>

					<p>
						The Machina Emblematica is a retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) 
						system, an AI application that combines vector-based search with natural 
						language responses generated by a Large Language Model. It uses data 
						from the 1668 edition of Symbola et Emblemata provided by the 
						<a href="https://www.digitale-sammlungen.de/en/details/bsb10575861" target="_blank">Münchener 
						Digitale Bibliothek</a>. When answering your questions, the Machina 
						draws information directly from the scanned images and transcribed pages.
					</p>

					<h2>Custodes Machinae.</h2>

					<ul>
						<li>
							<strong>Michela Vignoli</strong>, 
							<a href="https://www.ait.ac.at/" target="_blank">AIT Austrian Institute of Technology</a>
						</li>

						<li>
							<strong>Rainer Simon</strong>,
							<a href="https://rainersimon.io" target="_blank">rainersimon.io</a>
						</li>

						<li>
							<strong>Chiara Palladino</strong>, 
							<a href="https://www.furman.edu/academics/classics/" target="_blank">Furman University Classics</a>
						</li>

						<li>
							<strong>Kathryn Wilson</strong>, 
							<a href="https://www.furman.edu/academics/classics/" target="_blank">Furman University Classics</a>
						</li>
					</ul>
				</section>

				<section id="acknowledgements">
					<p>
						A project of scholarly curiosity, digital alchemy, and emblematic wonder. Made 
						possible by open access resources and a love of the obscure. The project received 
						funding from the BMBF joint project <a href="https://hermes-hub.de/" target="_blank">HERMES</a> and 
						the <a href="https://www.furman.edu/humanities-center/" target="_blank">Furman Humanities Center</a>.
					</p>
				</section -->
			</div>
		</main>
	</div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
	.app-wrapper {
		box-shadow: inset 0em 0em 10em rgb(0,0,0,0.5)
	}

	.bg-texture {
		position: absolute;
		top: 0;
		left: 0;
		width: 100%;
		height: 100%;

	}
</style>